		<div id="storycolumn">
          <p class="storyhead">Burn down the record store &mdash; buying rare music online</p>
          <p class="storykicker">From auction sites to specialist retailers, the rare music market has invaded cyberspace. David Winter explores online resources and traditional music-hunting tactics &ndash; and assembles some tips [link to tips] to help you find rare music online.</p>
          <p>Rare music collectors can emerge from specialist music stores, markets, op-shops and record fairs and go online to source goods. The internet provides easy access to many out-of-print records and hard to find CDs from around the world.</p>
          <p>Many music aficionados might shudder to imagine replacing hours digging though crates of records with the click of a mouse. But the convenience and choice online shopping provides draws many collectors to their computers, including Jacob Fischer.</p>
          <p>Jacob stockpiles 70s rock rarities &ndash; he boasts a collection numbering in the thousands. He turned to the internet four years ago when he couldn&rsquo;t find <a href="http://www.kraftwerk.com/">Kraftwerk&rsquo;s</a> obscure, out-of-print debut album in stores. </p>
          <p>Online, Jacob discovered that the album was briefly reissued on a now-defunct label. He then tracked down a seller in Vancouver and his album arrived within three weeks. Jacob now buys most of his music online.</p>
          <p>He hasn&rsquo;t completely abandoned the racks of albums and CDs in music stores though. &lsquo;You can&rsquo;t get everything on the Net,&rsquo; he says. &lsquo;It&rsquo;d be boring.&rsquo; He still frequents local music shops to chat with staff whose expert knowledge he finds helpful. &lsquo;I like talking to them about stock they&rsquo;re getting in, and looking through their racks for something <a href="../music/features/raremusic/raremusic2.html">obscure,&rsquo; Jacob says.&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</a></p>
